column11:
During my NYSC in Adamawa state in 2004, I volunteered as a missionary, giving my entire youth service to mission work on the mountains of Mubi amongst the Juluvu people in Lila and Liande. I have been a missionary since then. 

I remember the pain I felt and the tears I cried
column31:
During my NYSC in Adamawa state in 2004, I volunteered as a missionary, giving my entire youth service to mission work on the mountains of Mubi amongst the Juluvu people in Lila and Liande. I have been a missionary since then. 

I remember the pain I felt and the tears I cried when I saw how Boko Haram invaded Mubi. The devastation and mourning were too much for me. Nothing can describe the pain. 

If you have never lived as a Christian or engaged Christian ministry in Northern Nigeria, you may never understand the perils our brothers and sisters face. As bad as you imagine it is, your imagination does not come close to what it is in reality. 

I have repeatedly cried and begged the church in the south that if we do not rise and defend our brothers and sisters up north, they will stand in judgement against us on the last day. This isn't a call for one man to answer. This is a call for all of us to band together and let our brothers know that they are not alone. The enemy has become bolder and bolder because our brothers and sisters have been left alone in this battle for far too long. 

May God quicken us!!!

column11:
Your parents’ supports will take u far in life, and frankly it goes beyond financial support.
When I was abt to go for nysc, I went back home to tell my parents, my dad sat me down, said few words & prayed for me.
Bro, I can tell u, those words lead me to this point I’m today!

You have no excuse

column31:
We're Hiring 🔔 

People and Culture Intern

📍Lagos - Hybrid (2 days at the office)

Fresh out of school or in NYSC, and looking to do meaningful work that actually makes a difference?

We might be looking for you. If this sounds like you:

You're the kind of person who has lists… and enjoys ticking things off.

You’re naturally organized and love making processes better, smoother, faster.

You’re the behind-the-scenes engine that keeps things moving without needing to be in the spotlight.

You’re smart (and not afraid to say it), a quick learner, and you take pride in getting things done well and on time.

You’re curious about how companies grow and how People & Culture shapes everything behind the scenes from hiring to engagement to team dynamics.

Apply here 👇 https://t.co/f7k6DZmBkf

column11: @YKoluwaseun9 There’s this story my secondary school teacher shared with us back then. She was posted to Damaturu from Anambra for NYSC. On the way, their vehicle broke down in the middle of nowhere—no houses, no cars, nothing. They trekked till they found one small house and heard someone
column31:
There’s this story my secondary school teacher shared with us back then. She was posted to Damaturu from Anambra for NYSC. On the way, their vehicle broke down in the middle of nowhere—no houses, no cars, nothing. They trekked till they found one small house and heard someone calling “Ifeoma.” She was so happy, thinking she had found fellow Igbos.

When they got to the gate and explained their situation, the man switched to Hausa and told them straight up: “We’re not Igbos and you’re not welcome here.”

That was her first real Damaturu experience.

column11:
Hiring!!

HR Assistant (NYSC)

Locations: Lekki, Ikeja, Ibadan (Hybrid)
Employment Type: NYSC Internship

Job Summary
Voyatek Group is looking for a proactive HR Assistant (NYSC) to support daily HR operations, including recruitment, employee engagement, and administrative tasks.
column31:
Hiring!!

HR Assistant (NYSC)

Locations: Lekki, Ikeja, Ibadan (Hybrid)
Employment Type: NYSC Internship

Job Summary
Voyatek Group is looking for a proactive HR Assistant (NYSC) to support daily HR operations, including recruitment, employee engagement, and administrative tasks. The ideal candidate must be a serving corps member with at least 10 months remaining until their Passing Out Parade (POP). This role is perfect for individuals passionate about building a career in Human Resources within a dynamic work environment.

Requirements:
Must be a current NYSC corps member with at least 10 months left before POP.
A degree in Human Resources, Industrial Relations, Business Administration, or a related HR field.
Strong organizational and communication skills.
Proficiency in Microsoft Office (Excel, Word, PowerPoint).
Ability to handle confidential information professionally.

How to Apply
Send your resume to recruitment@voyatekgroup.com with the subject:
"Application – HR Assistant (NYSC) – [Lekki or Ibadan]

Need an NYSC Associate to join me at work. You will be assisting with everything related to business development, branding and corporate communications in a law firm.

Requirement: 
1. Must have graduated with a minimum of 2:1 in mass communication or any business related field. 
2. Can speak and write English Language fluently. 
3. Be very creative and marketing inclined (this will form a major part of the test)🙏🏻

Work environment and culture is fantastic and it’s a hybrid role. ✅

Please send a DM for more details and application email. Thanks

column31:
NYSC 2025 REGISTRATION UPDATE
🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨🚨
Good day, Prospective Corps Members. I hope you had a productive day. If you've successfully registered for the 2025 NYSC, you should see an update on your dashboard. The portal currently displays the following categories

1. Congratulations 🎊🍾 You have successfully registered for 2025 Batch A stream 2. You will be communicated in due course when to print your callup letter.

2. Congratulations! you have successfully registered for 2025 B(Means Batch B)

3. Empty Dashboard: Some users are seeing empty dashboards. 

I advise everyone to stay tuned and await further directives from @officialnyscng . While some have beens saying it technical issues, Well I believe NYSC would promptly address any glitches, considering their social media presence. 

With the appointment of a new Director-General, we can expect potential changes or new policies in the 2025 NYSC registration process. Notably, this year's registration has been smoother compared to previous batches, indicating a new implementation approach. So we should be expecting something new from NYSC

If you've noticed updates on your portal, I recommend preparing ahead and staying informed. @officialnyscng will provide updates in due course, and eligible individuals for Stream 1 will be notified accordingly.

Thank you

column31:
During NYSC, I was Platoon Leader of Platoon 1. I spoke against the system during one of the meetings with the State Director. I spoke without malice but with objectivity hoping that it would be impactful. 

Guess what?. I was the only platoon leader that wasn’t posted to Ibadan. I paid the price and was posted to ISEYIN. 

I cried my eyes out that day and I was the last to leave camp. To God be the glory, ISEYIN was the best thing that happened to me that year.

Try Google’s Fundamentals of Digital Marketing, try learning copywriting, or
column31:
I’ve been meaning to say something to people going for NYSC this time. Please, learn digital skills!!

I know virtual assistantship is in vogue now but you don’t have to learn that if you’re unable to.

Try Google’s Fundamentals of Digital Marketing, try learning copywriting, or how to run ads, even a foreign language like French, Spanish, Korean or German, etc. Just utilise your time towards something productive that’d bring good income later.

Don’t just go there and be gallivanting about because you finally got freedom away from your parents. You’ll regret it later and nobody will tell you sorry.🥺

column31:
Someone I took in for internship whilst she was awaiting Nysc. She one day suddenly informed me that she was quitting. It hit me because she was handling some things and attending meetings with me.

On one of such meetings, we concluded a deal and our client took us to a shoe store to get us each a pair of shoes.

Mind you, it was a paid internship. She didnt show gratitude for the internship till this year and this all occurred last year.

Anyways, she called to tell me that she wants to return. I asked her why was she not retained at the bigger firm and she said they told her some bullshit.

Well, I really don’t have space now and even if I did, she’s only asking to return because she wasn’t retained in her Nysc firm.

column11:

column31:
NYSC: The Reason Nigeria Has Not Fought a Second Civil War 

The National Youth Service Corp experience is one of the best things about being a Nigerian. Sadly, as natural complainers, many Nigerians do not appreciate the benefits of that one-year service. 

Let's start with the camp experience. It is probably the first time that many spoiled youths get to have a taste of regimented discipline. And that discipline is so crucial for character development and the formation of virtues.

You wake up at 5:30 AM, have a cold shower, and then go to the parade ground for morning drills. Then, you have a communal breakfast. The ice starts to melt. And ethnic and tribal differences begin to wane and fade as new friendships are forged. 

People from the South also begin to see that Hausa people are just as intelligent as them. And then, by the third day, they also become aware that there are more ethnicities in Northern Nigeria than there are in the South and not every Northerner is an Aboki. 

In the South, Northerners experience more culture shocks but eventually see that people are people and that Yan Kudu are not very different from them. They are not all area boys and yahoo yahoo. 

You eat local foods, learn some of the lingo, and escape camp to engage in extracurricular activities. 

By social night, many young men would have met their future wives. 

And then you leave camp for your place of primary assignment, and you notice something. You start to act out some of the disciplines you imbibed during your three weeks of camp. 

You arrive early for work (if only your parents could see you!). You are less cavalier and more polite. And then, you begin to blend with the locals while acquiring new skills. 

In a year, you will have gained discipline, better understood Nigeria, and have expertise that can spice up your resume/CV and make you the dream of employers. 

Since Tuesday, May 22, 1973, when the National Youth Service Corps was established via Decree Number 24, 15.6 million Nigerians have passed through that program. 

Those 15.6 million people have been responsible for the most inter-ethnic and cross-religious marriages in Nigeria. They have given birth to the first and subsequent sets of truly Nigerian children. 

Children who may have nowhere to go if Nigeria divides, and as a result, will work towards the nation's unity. 

If you wonder why Nigeria has not had a second civil war despite the Maitatsine Revolution, Sap Riots, the Zangon Kataf crisis, the June 12 annulment, the Abacha tyranny, Sharia Riots, Niger Delta Militancy, the Yar'adua impasse, the Boko Haram insurgency, and the #EndSARS riots, the answer is NYSC. 

The 8% of our population who went through the program, along with our armed forces, have been the stabilising force in the nation at any point in time. 

The thing is that in 2007, there was a baton exchange. For the first time in Nigeria's history, both the President (Umaru Musa Yar'adua) and his deputy (Dr. Goodluck Jonathan) were products of the National Youth Service Corps. 

May God bless General Yakubu Gowon, who came up with the scheme that took my father to Sokoto in 1974 as a young man who did not even know how to say "come" in Hausa. He did not return to Southern Nigeria until he became a Justice of the Court of Appeal who was fluent in Hausa and an expert in Sharia Law. 

In loving memory of my late father, Justice Jean Omokri, 1950-2010, seen here with his best friend, Justice Ibrahim Umar, at my call to bar party. 

Reno Omokri 
Tuesday, April 15, 2025.

column31:
Minister of Education Proposes 2-Year NYSC, Praises Scheme's Role in Tackling Certificate Fr@ud

Minister of Education, Dr. Maruf Olatunji Alausa, has proposed extending the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC) programme from one year to two years.

Speaking during a courtesy visit by the new NYSC Director-General, Brigadier General Olakunle Nafiu, in Abuja, the Minister suggested expanding the NYSC's Skill Acquisition and Entrepreneurship Development (SAED) programme to help corps members become job creators.

He also commended the NYSC for its digital registration process, which has curbed certificate fr@ud involving foreign-trained graduates within West Africa.

Additionally, Dr. Alausa addressed the unresolved issue of OND part-time graduates who obtained full-time HNDs but were previously exempted from national service.

In response, Brigadier General Nafiu praised the Minister's achievements in the education sector and called for the creation of a database for Nigerian youths studying abroad.

column31:
Would you encourage your sibling or child to join the Nigerian Army as an Igbo person?

I served in Sokoto State during my NYSC, I was posted to Giginya Barracks. I became friends with some high-ranking officers and gradually developed a love for military life. I even started considering a career in the armed forces.

When I spoke to one of the officers, a Fulani man, he told me bluntly that, as someone without ‘a father in heaven,’ he wouldn’t advise me to join the army as an Igbo person. According to him, I would be posted straight to Borno to fight Boko Haram.

So I ask again: would you genuinely send your own sibling or child to join the army, or are you only encouraging other people’s children to do so?

column31:
Unemployed Today, In-Demand Tomorrow: How Tech Changed My Life

Seyi sighed as he checked his email for the hundredth time that day, still no job offers. It had been six months since NYSC ended, and the rejection emails were piling up.

"We regret to inform you..." became the soundtrack of his life.
Every morning, he woke up early, dressed as if going to work, and sat in front of his old laptop searching for opportunities. But the jobs wanted experience, and he had none.

One afternoon, while scrolling through WhatsApp statuses, he saw a post: "Build your first mobile app with Flutter." He had heard of Flutter before, something about building apps with one codebase. Curious, he clicked the link.

At first, it was overwhelming. Dart? Widgets? State management? It felt like learning a new language. But after a few YouTube tutorials, things started to click. He set a goal: build a simple app in a month.
Days turned into nights as Seyi coded his first mobile app; a to-do list app with reminders. It wasn’t perfect, but it worked. Excited, he shared it on Twitter.

Unexpectedly, a startup founder in Lagos reached out:
“I love your app. Can you build something for my business?”
That one project turned into another. And another. Soon, Seyi was freelancing, earning in dollars, and working with clients worldwide.

The same companies that once ignored his CV?
Now they were in his inbox.

This week, choose growth. Choose possibility. Choose YOU. HAPPY NEW WEEK.

#TechSkills #TechJourney #mobileappdevelopment

column31:
Ex-NYSC DG, Gen Tsiga, Freed After 56 Days in K+dn@ppers' Den

Retired Brigadier-General Maharazu Tsiga, former Director-General of the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC), has regained his freedom after spending 56 days in c@ptivity.

Tsiga was k+dnapped on February 5, 2025, in Bakori Local Government Area of Katsina State, along with nine others. Despite his family paying a ransom, he remained in captivity for several more weeks before his eventual release.

Reports on the ransom amount vary, with some sources claiming N60 million was paid, while Daily Trust reports that the actual sum was three times higher. A family member revealed that after the ransom payment, the k+dnappers went silent for a week before allowing Tsiga to speak with his relatives. Though the abductors later demanded additional money, no further payments were made.

Tsiga was eventually released and is said to be in good health. Sources indicate he is being moved to Abuja from Zamfara State. A senior military official confirmed his release, while his family expressed relief over his safe return.

column31:
When Covid-19 hit. Social distancing, lockdowns, all the restrictions — it changed everything. Business slowed down. Eventually, we had to put things on hold, especially when I had to leave for NYSC in 2021.

After finishing NYSC in 2022, we gave it another shot, reopened the spot on campus in 2023. But juggling that with a 9 to 5 just wasn’t sustainable. It became clear I couldn’t manage both, and once again, we had to take a step back.

Fast forward to one year ago, April 11th, 2024 — we reopened as Ice Republic Fries and Grills at Energy Filling Station, Adebayo. That move wasn’t just about reopening, it was about starting fresh and rebuilding. And since then, we have been writing a new story.

column31:
SKILL UP FOR YOUR FUTURE!

Make Word of Righteousness Ventures (WORV) your PPA (Place of Primary Assignment) and gain relevant skills that will boost your employability in today's labour market. 

Do you know you can use your NYSC service year to gain relevant skill sets that will prepare you for the future, and give you a headstart in the labour market when you subscribe to our NYSC Skill Acquisition Programme (N-SAP) under WORV? 

With WORV N-SAP, Corp Members will be given the opportunity to learn, practise and master a number of technical skills relevant in today's world.

TECHNICAL TRAINING PACKAGES:
Corp Members will be trained on any of the following skills based on their preference:

1. Graphics Design 
2. Digital Marketing 
3. Sound and Audio Engineering 
4. Cinematography
5. Broadcasting Technology

APPLICATION PROCESS:
To apply to be part of WORV N-SAP, or for enquiry about the programme, please contact Olujuyigbe Omolade on 0803 688 4759 (WHATSAPP ONLY).

N-SAP IS AN EXPRESSION OF WORV, A SUBSIDIARY OF EGFM.

Signed:
WORV Management

Brigadier General Olakunle Oluseye Nafiu, the Director General of the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC), has announced that corps members will begin receiving a monthly allowance of N77,000 starting in March 2025. 

Speaking during an interactive session with corps members at https://t.co/C3vYD104mQ
column31:
Brigadier General Olakunle Oluseye Nafiu, the Director General of the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC), has announced that corps members will begin receiving a monthly allowance of N77,000 starting in March 2025. 

Speaking during an interactive session with corps members at the Wuse and Garki NYSC Zonal Offices in Abuja, Nafiu reassured them that the Federal Government and the NYSC remain committed to their welfare.

He emphasized that ensuring the well-being of corps members remains a top priority. The DG commended the selfless service of corps members and urged them to stay calm, dedicated, and disciplined in the discharge of their duties.

He also praised the visionaries behind the NYSC scheme and called on all stakeholders to continue supporting its objectives. Furthermore, he reiterated the NYSC’s commitment to instilling patriotism, discipline, leadership qualities, and teamwork among corps members. “From March, you will start receiving N77,000 as your monthly allowance.

When did pastors start defending politicians instead of truth? Or are you now officially ordained in the ministry of sycophancy?

You’re mocking Raye because she spent ₦1.2 million in Tinubu’s failed economy? Does that mean her criticism is invalid? Are you okay? So now, in your warped mind, no one should complain about a broken system unless they’re barefoot and begging? That’s like saying a man can’t criticize bad roads because he owns a car. The fact that people are still trying to survive doesn’t mean the economy isn’t in shambles.

Let’s not pretend, this economy is choking everyone except the thieves looting it. Bread is a luxury. Fuel is madness. Power supply is a ghost. The Naira is on life support. But instead of addressing the real issues, you’re online cyberstalking a young woman and making sarcastic remarks about her finances? That’s not just creepy, it’s pathetic.

You think saying, “I guess it’s from the ₦77k too?” makes you sound smart? No, it exposes you as another bitter, insecure man who can’t stand to see a young woman speak truth without shaking. You’re not angry at what she said, you’re angry she said it confidently without needing permission from cowards like you.

And for the record, Raye doesn’t owe you or anyone an explanation for how she spends her money. If she worked, hustled, saved, or even got gifts, that’s her business, not yours. Your fake outrage says more about your empty pride than her shopping ever could.

You’re used to people staying silent while things burn. Raye is not one of those people. She’s the voice of a generation that’s done being polite about suffering. So while you hide behind a pulpit and defend failure, she’s out here holding power accountable. That’s what real leadership looks like, not licking the boots of corrupt politicians.

So here’s some advice, Pastor: go back to your congregation and preach to your tithes. Leave Raye alone. She’s not your church member. She’s not your business. And she damn sure isn’t scared of your clout chasing sermons.

She said what she said and she was right. Tinubu’s economy is trash.

Deal with it.

[8:00AM]
#Agege
#TrafficReports 
Fast moving traffic on Old Abeokuta road from Abbatoir down to New garage. Connecting Nitel down to Total underneath the bridge is slow due to alternation and pedestrian crossing.
Old ipaja road from NYSC inward Olufunlayo down to Agbotikuyo is good but slow from Shofunde inward Okekoto due to alternation and ongoing road rehabilitation.
Alfa Nla inward Oniwaya junction down to Capitol is good.
Mangoro Ashade inward Akanni Doherty is slow due to Traffic light alternation but  movement to connect Guinness.
Pen Cinema bridge inward Oba Ogunji is good with minor delay at Odo Eran due to alternation.
Metal box inward Acme junction down to Fumec is gathering momentum.
Akilo inward Mobil Ashade connecting Oba Akran down to Dangote U turn is good. 
No overnight Impediment recorded.
Officers are on ground doing the needful.

After earning her first degree, completing NYSC, and gaining work experience, Dr. Fasawe boldly https://t.co/SeaojTpPki
column31:
We also celebrated remarkable journeys of purpose and passion, and Dr. Oluwaseun Fasawe’s story stood out as an example of what it means to pursue your calling with intention. 

After earning her first degree, completing NYSC, and gaining work experience, Dr. Fasawe boldly decided to return to the classroom and chase her lifelong dream of becoming a doctor. “Returning to study medicine was my best decision,” she said. “And I’m beyond excited that I made that move.” 

With hands-on learning and a deeply practical experience at Bowen, she thrived — especially in Obstetrics and Gynaecology, where she emerged as the best student. Now, she’s set her sights on specializing in the field, determined to make a lasting impact on women’s healthcare in Nigeria. 

Dr. Fasawe’s journey proves that it’s never too late to follow your purpose, and Bowen University strives to provide that atmosphere to thrive in innovative learning in Nigeria and beyond. 

Congratulations @ReniFasawe, we're rooting for you ALL the way 👏🏾👏🏾

#BowenUniversity #WomenInMedicine #MedicalInduction #BowenPride

column31:
Job Alert ‼️ 

Graphic Designer at Labile
📍Remote

Required:
At least a Bachelor’s degree in any discipline.
Must have completed NYSC.
Minimum of 3+ years of experience in a graphic design role, experience with a media agency or creative studio is a plus.
Portfolio demonstrating diversification in different niches  is preferred.
Advanced proficiency in Adobe Creative Suite (Photoshop, Illustrator, InDesign, After Effects) Figma, PremierePro and Canva.
Experience designing for multiple clients, adapting content to different formats, and ensuring high-quality output.
Experience handling multiple client projects, tailoring designs to different industries and brand identities.
Ability to use data and audience insights to refine creative strategies and optimize design performance.
Understanding of typography, layout principles, and color theory for effective brand storytelling.

See full JD and apply via this link:
https://t.co/A0dusDEJSZ

NYSC Tips for Recent Graduates

column31:
NYSC Tips for Recent Graduates 

Every year, I get questions from younger colleagues or mentees about how to make the most of their NYSC year - especially when it comes to getting a solid place of primary assignment (PPA). 
I have always shared tips via DMS, but I thought to share here as I believe it can benefit many:

1. Be Proactive — Don’t Wait to Be Posted Somewhere You Don’t Like.

Start by identifying a list of organisations you admire and would love to work with. Cold email them  - yes, just shoot your shot. In your email, introduce yourself, mention your course of study, the skills you’ve developed, and the kind of value you’re willing to bring. Go a step further: review their work, identify gaps, and suggest ways you can help improve their workflow or contribute to specific projects. That initiative can go a long way. If you get a positive response, it can even help you influence your NYSC posting to that state or sector.

2. Use the NYSC Camp Strategically.

If you end up posted to a random state, camp isn’t just for parades. Join a CDS (Community Development Service) group that aligns with your interests — like SDGs, Climate Change, Education, ICT, or Legal Aid. Then reach out to the group coordinators and pitch yourself. These coordinators often know which organisations are actively looking for capable corps members and can help with PPA placements for select CDS members.

3. For Media and Journalism Enthusiasts — OBS is Your Friend.

For those interested in media, content creation, or journalism, joining the Orientation Broadcasting Service (OBS) during camp is never out of fashion. It’s a fantastic space to network, hone your storytelling or on-air skills, and build relationships that could influence your PPA. A lot of corps members who join OBS get priority placement and better exposure — take it seriously.

4. Think Beyond NYSC — Use the Year to Launch Bigger Moves.

If you’re thinking of applying for scholarships or opportunities abroad, don’t panic if you’re posted to a less-than-ideal state. As long as you have access to the internet, you can use the year to build. Apply for fully funded scholarships, write and polish your Statement of Purpose (SOP), and reach out to institutions and professors globally.

Your teaching experience (which is common for corps members) can actually be a big asset abroad — especially when applying for assistantships. It’s all about how you tailor your value and tell your story. One NYSC year is more than enough to reposition your life.

Bottom line? Treat NYSC not just as a service year, but as a launchpad.
Be deliberate. Be strategic. You’re not just serving - you are setting the foundation for what comes next.

Feel free to share with someone who might need this.

#YouWillNotFail

column31:
DHQ PRESS RELEASES 

MILITARY OPERATION FACILITATED FORMER NYSC DG GENERAL MAHARAZU TSIGA'S RELEASE 

The attention of Defence Headquarters ( DHQ) has been drawn to a misleading article by Brigadier General Ismaila Abdullahi which claims that military generals contributed money to secure the recent release of Brigadier General Mahrazu Tsiga (retired) who was held captive for 56 days. This article clearly contradicts the efforts made by troops of Operation Fansan Yamma by embarking on Search and Rescue Operation to secure the release of the Brigadier General Mahrazu Tsiga (retired) in addition to other non-kinetic efforts.

The publication includes an appreciation message from the senior officer, thanking other senior officers and civilian counterparts for their material and other support that contributed to the rescue of the former Director General of the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC).

While it may seem unproductive to engage with those who consistently criticize the military especially those that have benefited from the same military, it is essential to clarify the relentless efforts undertaken by the troops that facilitated General Tsiga's release.

It is important to note that the unfortunate abduction of the former DG of NYSC occurred in the wee hours of 6 February 2025, in Tsiga, Kafur District of Bakori Local Government Area in Katsina State. Immediately, troops of 17 Brigade were alerted, they responded to the situation around 0300 hours the same day and in a commendable show of professionalism, swiftly went on pursuit in conjunction with the Air Component of Operation Fansan Yamma. These combined efforts led to troops combing the assailants’/bandits hideouts within Jeka, Areda, and Zango, all in Kankara Local Government Area, in search of the former DG. The operation extended to Ruwan Lafiya, Mununu, Matallawa and Bakkai in Faskari Local Government Area. Although no direct contact was made with the abductors, the troops successfully pressured the criminals, who abandoned rustled animals and some captives in their hasty retreat. The troops nevertheless sustained the pursuit of the terrorists with unwavering determination, despite facing difficulties due to challenging terrain.

On 8 February, leveraging credible intelligence, troops intensified their manhunt for the abductors and conducted dawn attacks at Yankuzo and Gidan Dankaka in Tsafe Local Government Area of Zamfara State where terrorist kingpin Ado Aliero hibernates. More so, intelligence confirmed that he had links with the abductors. Unfortunately, the operations did not result in locating the terrorists. However, subsequent air operations at Dunya Hill, a suspected bandit stronghold where General Tsiga was held, disrupted the terrorists, leading to the escape of several captives. Regrettably, the former DG was unable to escape due to health concerns. One of the captives, Barau Garba, a teacher at Government Secondary School in Tsiga and who was with General Tsiga was rescued by troops  and he shared his experience via the attached video. Barau has since been reunited with his family in Tsiga town. In another instance, troops assaulted Pauwa Hills and Matallawa area of Kankara Local Government Area in search of Brigadier General Tsiga. However, they were only able to rescue 84 kidnapped victims from the area without locating him. In the process, several terrorists/bandits were neutralised while 3 personnel sustained gunshot wounds.

Since Brigadier General Tsiga's abduction on 7 February 2025, troops have remained relentless in their pursuit, conducting both air and ground operations within Danmusa, Kankara and Faskari Local Government Areas where he was supposedly held captive at different times and these operations kept pressure on the abductors. It is thus only fair to recognize the significant sacrifices made by these troops who have worked day and night, often at great risk to their own lives in their search of the senior officer.

column31:

Location: Abuja (FCT)

Candidates should possess an HND / Bachelor's Degree in Accounting or Finance.

Working knowledge of tax. Knowledge, Skills and Abilities.
Strong Administrative skills, including proficiency with MS Office applications.
Analytical thinker with detailed research proficiency Fantastic organizational skills and detail oriented.
Ability to work under pressure and meet deadlines.

Method of Application 
Send CV to: hr@abujaclinics.com using the Job Title as the subject of the mail.

column31:
MILITARY OPERATION FACILITATED GENERAL MAHARAZU TSIGA'S RELEASE - DHQ

The  Defence Headquarters has reacted to a misleading article  claiming  that military generals contributed money to secure the recent release of Brigadier General Mahrazu Tsiga, former director NYSC who was held captive for 56 days. 

In a statement,the director defence information brigadier general Tukur Gusau says,the  article clearly contradicts the efforts made by troops of Operation Fansan Yamma who embarked on Search and rescue Operation to secure the release of the Brigadier General Mahrazu Tsiga.

 leveraging on credible intelligence , the statement notes,  troops intensified  manhunt  for the abductors in suspected bandits hideouts in Zamfara state  conducting  attacks in addition to air operations  leading to the escape of several persons abducted together with Gen Tsiga 

  The  search for  Brigadier General Tsiga in several other areas led  to the  successful rescue of  84 kidnapped victims and many bandits eliminated.

The Director Defence information stressed that, it is only  fair to recognize the significant sacrifices  by troops at great risk in search of  the senior officer who were relentless since the abduction  on 7 February 2025, in their pursuit within areas where he was supposedly held captive at different times.

column31:
Minister Proposes 2-Year NYSC Service: A Call for Reform or a Missed Opportunity?

JUST IN – Nigeria's Minister of Education, Dr. Maruf Olatunji Alausa, has proposed the extension of the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC) from one year to two years. He made this suggestion during a courtesy visit by the newly appointed Director-General of NYSC, Brigadier General Olakunle Nafiu.

Dr. Alausa's comments have sparked a wave of reactions across the country, with many Nigerians questioning the rationale behind extending a scheme that, in their view, is already faltering in purpose and implementation.

A Historical Perspective

The NYSC was established in 1973 by General Yakubu Gowon in the aftermath of the Nigerian Civil War. The vision was simple yet profound: to promote national unity and integration by sending graduates to states outside their region of origin. It was meant to foster cultural exchange, reduce ethnic division, and build a stronger Nigerian identity.

Over the years, millions of Nigerian youths have participated in the scheme. However, the reality today starkly contrasts with its founding ideals.

The Current State of NYSC

Insecurity, corruption, and systemic inefficiencies have undermined the program. With the rise in kidnappings, terrorism, and communal clashes in many parts of the country, many corps members now reject postings to certain states due to safety concerns. Reports indicate that up to 40% of corps members 'work out' their postings to more comfortable and secure areas, often with financial inducements.

Furthermore, the quality of placements has drastically declined. Many graduates are deployed to schools or offices with no real structure, no mentorship, and little to no impact. For many, the service year has become a formality, rather than an enriching national assignment.

The Two-Year Proposal: Solution or Setback?

While Dr. Alausa’s intentions may be rooted in a desire to enhance the impact of NYSC, proposing a two-year mandatory service period raises critical questions:

What value does an additional year bring when the current structure is failing?

Can the government afford it? With over 300,000 graduates mobilized annually, the cost of stipends, logistics, training, and administration would double – an enormous burden on an already strained budget.

What about the job market? Extending the service year further delays entry into the workforce and may aggravate the already high youth unemployment rate, which currently stands at over 40%.

A Smarter Alternative: Reform, Not Extension

Rather than prolonging a flawed system, a reimagining of NYSC is long overdue. One practical approach would be to retain the three-week orientation camp, which offers a rare moment of cultural exchange and discipline, but scrap the remaining months of the service year in its current form.

Instead, the government should redirect NYSC resources to provide startup capital and business training for corps members. If each graduate received a lump sum – equivalent to the total amount the government would have spent over the service year – it could jumpstart careers, fuel entrepreneurship, and reduce dependency.

For instance, if each corps member currently receives N33,000 monthly for 12 months, that's nearly N400,000 per person, not including allowances, housing, and logistics. Channeling this directly into micro-loans, skill acquisition, or business grants could yield greater socio-economic impact.

column31:
IMPORTANT NOTICE TO PCMS PREPARING FOR 2025 NYSC BATCH A STREAM 1

This guide provides step-by-step instructions on creating a #profile on the NYSC portal, a crucial step in the registration process.

👉Step 1: Access the NYSC Portal
Visit the NYSC portal using the link: 

https://t.co/9Xew43sfsG

👉Step 2: Wait for Registration Activation

Note that the registration portal will be activated on April 7, 2025, and will remain open until April 11, 2025. During this period, the portal will display "MOBILIZATION BATCH A, 2025" along with the registration dates.

👉Step 3: Select Registration Option

Choose from the following options:
🔰Fresh Registration (for first-time users)
🔰Revalidation (for those who were deployed in the previous batch but didn't report)

👉Step 4: Create an Account

For first-time users, click on "Fresh Registration" and:

- Input your valid email address
- Create a password
- Confirm your password {Please remember your password. It will be used for subsequent visits to the portal}🧏‍♂️🧏
- Choose a security question and answer

👉Step 5: Verify Your Account

Click "Continue" and check your email for a confirmation email from NYSC. Click the verification link sent to your email to activate your account.

👉 Step 6: Fill Pre Payment Page
This page you are to fill the following details
Email, Country of Study, Name of Institution, Jamb Registration Number, Matric No, Programme, Password, GSM no, Surname, First Name, Middle Name, Class of Degree, Date of graduation(Check Senate list.
🟢Agree that the information provided is valid

column31:
PRESS RELEASE

EDUCATION MINISTER ADVOCATES SKILL-FOCUSED NYSC REFORM TO EQUIP YOUTH FOR MARKET RELEVANCE AND NATIONAL DEVELOPMENT

The Honourable Minister of Education, Dr. Maruf Olatunji Alausa, has described Nigerian youth as the nation’s most valuable resource for driving progress in education, healthcare, and economic development. He made this known during a courtesy visit by the Director-General of the National Youth Service Corps (NYSC), Brigadier General Olakunle Akinyemi Nafiu, and his delegation to the Federal Ministry of Education headquarters in Abuja.

 Dr. Alausa suggestion of several key initiatives, including the Teacher’s Call—a programme aimed at engaging NCE holders as temporary teachers in underserved areas; the Rural Health Corps—designed to deploy corps members with medical training to rural communities; and a comprehensive reform of the NYSC orientation programme to incorporate vocational, entrepreneurial, agricultural, and ICT training to boost youth employability and reduce unemployment.

Underscoring his passion for skill acquisition and youth empowerment, the Honourable Minister further proposed an extension of the National Youth Service year beyond the current 12 months. He noted that such an extension would serve as a strategic solution to unemployment by offering young Nigerians more time to acquire market-ready skills. According to him, this initiative would enable corps members to make more meaningful contributions to national development while enhancing their employability and entrepreneurial potential.

He then re affirmed his belief in the potentials of Nigeria youth as the greatest asset for advancing education and economic growth which can not be underestimated.

Also speaking, the Honourable Minister of State for Education, Professor Suwaiba Said Ahmad, applauded the NYSC for its pivotal role in maintaining educational standards and safeguarding the integrity of academic certificates, particularly amid rising concerns surrounding transnational education.

In his welcome address, the Permanent Secretary of the Ministry, Mr. Abel Olumuyiwa Enitan, commended both Honourable Ministers and the NYSC leadership for their shared vision and renewed commitment to collaboration. He described the visit as a timely convergence of ideas that will drive sustainable solutions in education and youth development.

In his response, Brigadier General Nafiu expressed appreciation for the Ministry’s continued partnership and outlined ongoing reforms within the NYSC aimed at improving service delivery. He advocated for the establishment of a pre-departure database to monitor Nigerian students studying abroad, tackle certificate fraud, and uphold the integrity of qualifications.

The Director-General also lauded the Skills Acquisition and Entrepreneurship Development (SAED) programme and called for continued collaboration with the Ministry to strengthen education and youth empowerment.

Both the Ministry and the NYSC leadership reaffirmed their joint commitment  to reforms anchored on integrity, innovation, and youth-driven transformation.

Boriowo Folasade 
Director Press & PR
5/4/25

column31: Yes, it’s true that the Nigerian Minister of Education, Dr. Maruf Olatunji Alausa, proposed extending the NYSC from one to two years on April 4, 2025. He also praised the NYSC for reducing certificate fraud via digital registration and addressed HND graduate exemptions, making them eligible. It’s still a proposal, not yet implemented, per reports on April 5, 2025.

The NCE-Teacher's Corps, great idea!
This extension is a NO-NO!!!!

Privately owned organisations rarely ask for the NYSC Certificate,make it optional 
@DrTunjiAlausa

column31:
Random guy reached out to me during the week to ask for salary negotiation tips😅.

Fresh out of Uni, and hasn’t even done NYSC yet, he interviewed for an IT role with a supposed pay of 800k/month and went through the process seamlessly but got a lowball offer of 500k.

He said he believed they did so because they knew he was young and thought he would still accept it that way.

Walked him through the back and forth negotiations spanning 2 days, and he’s walking away with 1M/month🤣

My biggest win this week fr.

HR / Recruiter no be your friend o, just know.

column31:
Position: Client Relations Personnel
Location: Lagos Island
Salary: ₦350,000 monthly
Availability: Candidate must be available to resume immediately.

Requirements:
•2–3 years post-NYSC experience in customer relations or client experience roles within a structured corporate environment

•Must reside on or have very easy access to Lagos Island

Key Skills and Qualities:
•Strong analytical and problem-solving skills
•Proficiency in data analysis and interpretation for reporting and decision-making
•High attention to detail and data accuracy
•Excellent written, verbal, and phone communication skills
•Proficiency in Microsoft Office and CRM software
•Sound understanding of customer engagement channels and tools
•Experience with sales or marketing interfaces is an added advantage
•High emotional intelligence and strong interpersonal skills
•Ability to manage sensitive client information with confidentiality and professionalism

Key Responsibilities:
•Manage and enhance the customer journey across online and offline platforms
•Respond promptly and professionally to all client communications
•Handle inquiries, complaints, and feedback, ensuring effective resolution
•Analyze and process customer data to provide actionable insights and support continuous improvement
•Document client interactions and feedback for internal use and improvement
•Work closely with other departments to ensure smooth service delivery
•Maintain accurate records of client information and ensure data security

To Apply: Send your CV and a brief cover letter to theclientofficerrecruitment@gmail.com with the subject line: Client Relations Personnel.

column31:
This is Day 2 😪 (feeling overwhelmed). I wasn’t consistent in applying for jobs because of NYSC but I still applied to two and the proposals got viewed, so I must be doing something right 🥹

There’s no how you won’t get results if you’re doing it the right way. I haven’t gotten hired yet but I know I will soon. I know it can be overwhelming but it’s definitely going to be alright.

I made a couple of Upwork videos that I’ll be sharing soon. Hopefully it helps someone.

The most important thing as a freelancer is to do proper research on whatever platform you’re on. Don’t just dive in without knowing how to use it. That’s the mistake most people make.

column31:
Brig.-Gen. Maharazu Tsiga (rtd), former NYSC DG, was freed on April 2, 2025, after 56 days in captivity. Kidnapped on February 5 in Katsina State, he was rescued alongside 18 others, including ex-Ambassador Gideon Yohanna, in an operation led by Maj.-Gen. Adamu Laka under the coordination of NSA Malam Nuhu Ribadu.

Tsiga described brutal conditions—scorpions, beatings, salt-laden food despite his hypertension, and even hyenas circling their mountain hideout. A failed rocket trap planted beneath him underscored the captors’ cruelty.

The rescue highlights Ribadu’s quiet but effective leadership through the NCTC. His efforts, praised by Yohanna, are yielding results across states like Zamfara, Katsina, Sokoto, and Niger. As Tsiga said, “The good ones will continue to live” a nod to Ribadu’s resolve in safeguarding Nigerians.

PICTURES: NSA Reunites Ex-NYSC DG and 18 Kidnapped Victims to CDS The National Security Adviser 
Mallam Nuhu Ribadu, has handed over 19 kidnapped victims, including former NYSC Director-General Ambassador Gideon Yohanna and retired Brigadier-General Maharazu Tsiga, to Chief of Defence Staff General Christopher Musa. The handover took place at the National Counter Terrorism Centre in Abuja.

Experience in brand identity, marketing materials, and social media content creation
Motion graphics and animation skills are a must
Excellent time management and creativity under tight deadlines
Preferred Candidate: Lives on the Island for easier office commute.

Send your CV and portfolio to hr@baselinksng.com with the subject line: Graphic & Motion Designer Application.

Join a dynamic team and work on exciting projects in a creative environment!

Location: Amuwo-Odofin Lagos,

column31:
*Symphony Developer needed at CashXpress Nigeria Limited*
Location: Amuwo-Odofin Lagos,
Employment Type: Full-time
Requirements

* A Bachelor's Degree in Computer Science, or any related field is required.
* Must have served (NYSC).
* 3+ years of experience in PHP programming with Symphony (5+ for senior roles).
* Programming experience with PHP version 8.
* Experience with PHP framework Symphony and its packages:
* Doctrine;
* Dependency Injection
* Validator
* Event Dispatcher
* Messenger
* API Platform
* Experience with MySQL, Redis, Rabbit MQ.
* Knowledge of REST API.
* Experience with Git, Gitlab CI/CD (nice to have for a middle, a must for a senior).
* Understanding of unit/functional/integration testing and experience in writing tests (PHPUnit).
* Experience in developing and maintaining applications in a microservices architecture (nice to have for a middle, a must for a senior).
* Experience with SWAGGER – API description, generation, and SDK usage (nice to have for a middle, a must for a senior).
* Experience with Docker/docker compose (nice to have for a middle, a must for a senior).
* Knowledge of coding standards and adherence to them.
* Understanding of SOLID and DDD (must).
* Experience with Scrum is to your advantage.
How to Apply
Inerested and qualified candidates should send their CV to hr@cashx.ng using the the “Symphony PHP Developer Application”. as the subject of the email.
